Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Cattle specifically are the primary sources of enterohemorrhagic _E. coli_ to humans. Other animals may carry the toxigenic bacterial strains, but the more liquid nature of bovine feces ("cow pies") facilitates contamination of the environment and the animals themselves.

Although classically associated with undercooked ground beef, the organisms can be acquired by ingestion of contaminated produce such as sprouts, salad greens and tomatoes, which can be contaminated anywhere along the food chain from the field to the kitchen. Other methods of acquisition include contamination of community water supplies as well as recreational water and direct exposure to infected animals and their environment such as in a petting zoo.

It is not stated what the livestock exposure was thought to be, but some of the cases appear to be child-to-child transmission, which occurs commonly in a household or day care setting. - Mod.LL

